    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-04-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-04-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="1050"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1050">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.113/388.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 13, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I have the honor to transmit
                    herewith, for your information, a copy of a letter dated April 11 from the
                    Attorney General requesting that, in the future, this Department <pb facs="0899"
                        n="783" xml:id="pg_783"/> handle the correspondence relating to exceptions
                    from the prohibition of your proclamation of March 14, 1912, of shipments to
                    Mexico of dynamite for industrial purposes.</p>
                <p>I also have the honor to inclose a copy of the reply which this Department is
                    making to the Attorney General to-day.</p>
                <p>This Department is entirely willing to handle this matter and to prepare the
                    correspondence relating to individual exceptions of shipments of dynamite that
                    has heretofore been prepared by the Attorney General, provided this arrangement
                    meets with your approval.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
